POSTED ON 3-27-20 --- MNCS Distance Learning Procedures (Revised 3/26/20)

Student Expectations for Distance Learning (Secondary)
Revised 3/26/20
Students are expected to continue their educational work during scheduled school days and hours per the MNCS 2019-20 calendar. Daily distance learning will consist of:
Attend daily remote advisory meetings between 8:15-10:00am (depending on schedule by advisors). This is a required check-in to be considered in attendance for the day. 
Maintain consistent electronic contact with their advisor to plan and demonstrate learning, and to resolve technology issues when needed (emails, phone calls, text msg, online chats/conferences, etc.). 
Log or otherwise document 150 minutes of individual project work, as well as 30 minutes of writing (daily journals, time logs, emails, reflections, writing prompts, capstone research papers, etc.)
Complete and document 45 minutes of math work daily.
Complete and document 45 minutes of sustained silent reading daily. Reading groups will continue to be scheduled from 12:05-12:50 daily.
Continue to participate in and document a minimum of 30 minutes of healthy daily activity (walks, runs, mindfulness, hacky sack, etc.)
Participate in electronic meetings with Sophomore, Junior, and Senior Teams as required.
The specific needs of each student who receives special education services is outlined in the student's Individual Education Plan (IEP). During the COVID-19 closure, special education teachers will be in contact with students and/or parents on a daily basis to ensure the continuity of service is provided to the extent possible. Students with IEPs will continue to receive special education and related services. Special education teachers will continue to address individual IEP goals, and the relevant accommodations and modifications outlined in a student's IEP will be in place to ensure participation in a distance learning environment.

Recommended Distance Learning Daily Schedule:
8:15-9:00am - Advisory
9:00-9:45 - Math Work
9:45-11:30 - Wellness/Project Work Time
11:30-12:05 - Lunch
12:05 - 12:50 - Reading Groups/Individual Quiet Reading Time
12:50-3:05 - Project Work Time/PE/Time logs and daily documentation

Advisor Expectations for Distance Learning (Secondary)
Advisors are expected to be available and responsive to students between the hours of 8 am to 3 pm Monday through Friday on school days as scheduled per the MNCS 2019-20 school calendar. 3pm to 4:30pm are reserved for administrative functions.
Students must have communication with their licensed teacher DAILY (MDE requirement)
Advisors will need to work actively to help students resolve issues related to technology and distance learning.
Daily advisor scheduling will consist of:
Holding advisory meetings daily between 8:15-10:00am using available tools. 
Be available during contact hours through phone call, text and email.
Monitor student math progress in ALEKS and be available for math assistance from 9:00-9:45am daily and as scheduling permits.
Schedule proposal team meetings in accordance with our 19-20 proposal team schedule
Monitor student work through individual meetings, time logs and journals, google docs, etc. and communicate individual progress to parents/guardians on a regular basis.

Student Expectations for Distance Learning (Elementary)
Revised 3/26/20
Students are expected to complete daily assignments and project work from the distance learning menus provided by your teacher.
Students (with help from parent/guardian as needed) will submit evidence of completed assignments to their teacher daily. Follow specific directions from your teacher on how to submit this evidence. 
Students will be in contact with their teacher on a regular basis. Teachers will have specific office hours for general help as well. 
The specific needs of each student who receives special education services is outlined in the student's Individual Education Plan (IEP). During the COVID-19 closure, Special Education teachers will be in contact with students and/or parents on a daily basis to ensure the continuity of service is provided to the extent possible. Teacher Expectations for Distance Learning (Elementary)
Create/update distance learning menus and educational materials, and supply them to students as needed.
Provide feedback to students on submitted work. Provide regular progress reports to parents/guardians. 
Maintain consistent office hours. Be available for students and parents via phone, web conferencing, and email from 8:15-3:00pm daily. 

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
HONEYWELL INSTANT ALERT --- sent out on Thursday, March 26th at 1:30 pm

Coronavirus Update ---- School Remains Closed ---
Brace yourselves everyone. This is going to be a super long message.
 
CLICK THIS LINK FOR A SPECIAL “VIDEO” MESSAGE READING, FEATURING ONE OF YOUR FAVORITE MNCS PEOPLE :: https://www.loom.com/share/c24811ed73c1429082d664f403ad12eb

As you probably are already aware, yesterday afternoon Governor Walz issued an executive order directing Minnesotans to stay home starting this Friday, March 27th through Friday, April 10th.

In addition to this stay-at-home order, the Minnesota Department of Education Commissioner Mary Cathryn Ricker has ordered that all Minnesota public school districts and charter schools begin providing Distance Learning instruction to students starting Monday, March 30th and continue until at least May 4th. Minnesota New Country School will begin providing Distance Learning instruction for our students starting Monday, March 30th, as directed. Parents should be receiving or have received information from your child’s teacher(s) by the end of the day tomorrow, Friday, March 27th on how to connect next Monday, as well as your child’s learning goals.

MNCS will be following our 2019-20 Calendar as planned. If changes are made to the calendar, we will notify you. Please refer to www dot new country school dot com as the source of information going forward. 

At both the Elementary and High School Buildings, we still have a lot of students' personal belongings. We understand the challenge of traveling right now, but we need you to come and pick these items up as soon as possible. Please contact your Advisor or Classroom Teacher to set up a time to do this. Only MNCS students will be allowed in the buildings. If needed, we will meet parents at the door with belongings. 

Thank you to all families for your help as MNCS works to provide these Distance Learning instruction plans to our students while keeping people safely in your homes. Our hope is that our MNCS Distance Learning instruction plans focus on Connection Over Content and provide Flexibility for our families and students. 

Please remain alert to any additional information that may be provided to parents and students by our school, including our Distance Learning instruction plans. In order to prevent the spread of the COVID-19 virus to the many vulnerable individuals in our community, we would also ask that everyone give their complete cooperation to Governor Walz’s Stay Home Minnesota executive order.

Take care everyone, enjoy the beautiful sunshine, and stay safe out there. Good Bye.

------------------------------------------------

Our MNCS Distance Learning Plans are being designed around the following Guiding Principles:
	-- Connection over content
-- Less is more
-- Designed flexibility for families
-- Monitor, evaluate, and respond

We understand we are making an unprecedented change to the education system and believe the designed learning activities will be successful at home. If your child(ren)’s assigned school work becomes overwhelming for your family, please contact your child(ren)’s advisor immediately. Please know our intent is not to burden any family, and staff would be happy to adjust as needed. If there is anything we can do to help, please reach out to your advisor. During the stay-at-home period, MNCS staff will be available by email during regular school hours (8:15a-3:00p) on Monday through Friday.

Attendance will be taken daily, Monday through Friday, during this “distance learning” period. Advisors will be “taking attendance” which will be based on a daily connection and communication between advisors and their students and/or families. A Message From Kylie Kuhlman ~ MNCS Elementary School Social Worker: 
I know that a lot of us are feeling a mix of emotions as we navigate school closure and life in the times of Covid-19. I have created a website with resources for kids and parents. It's loaded with information -- Links, videos, articles, calming tools, community resources. Please check it out and contact me if you need additional resources or help, or if you just want to connect. Find it here: http://mskylie-mncs.weebly.com/ Take care, be well! ~Ms. Kylie

REPOSTED ON 3.20.20 -- HONEYWELL INSTANT ALERT originally sent out on 3-18-20 ---- 
This is a message from MNCS and a request for assistance from Minnesota New Country School families: 

PLEASE PICK UP ALL BELONGINGS:
 MONDAY, MARCH 23RD OR TUESDAY, MARCH 24TH 
BETWEEN HOURS OF 7A - 7P

This is a message from MNCS and a request for assistance from Minnesota New Country School families. ----- We are preparing for the possibility of an extended school closure that could go well-beyond the current closure of March 27th. Students will need to have their learning materials at home, and we would like to begin thoroughly disinfecting the school building over the next several days. In order to accomplish both of these necessary steps, we are asking elementary and high school students to retrieve all of their belongings. Both buildings will be open Monday, March 23rd and Tuesday, March 24th from 7 am to 7 pm. Only students will be allowed to enter the building. ------- They are encouraged to bring large containers or multiple bags to hold all personal belongings and school materials. We are asking everyone to quickly empty these spaces so that they can be thoroughly cleaned. ------- If a student of any age has medication in the Nurse’s Office, the student should ask the staff person on duty for that medication and they will release it to the parent or guardian outside. ------- If you are unable to pick up your materials during these times, please contact your advisor or teacher to make alternate arrangements. ------- And finally, if you or your child are ill, or suspect that you may be ill, please do not enter the buildings at this time. Thank you and take care everyone.

Food Resources for MNCS kids & families: 
Lunch is available to MNCS kids and any kid under 18yrs-old, whether or not they qualify for free & reduced lunches, in the school district in which they live. This is similar to the Summer Lunch Program where all kids can get a meal who show up. If you are unable to travel to these food-lunch-breakfast distribution school sites, please contact Trish #507-868-0071 x0 or taustin@newcountryschool.com for other food options and add’l resources. This news article (southerminn link below) info about lunch-breakfast-meal offerings / times / locations for MNCS kids who live in and near these towns:

** South Elementary - 1405 S. 7th St. - Meals distributed 7:30a-9:00a and 11:00a-12:45p. Both breakfast and lunch may be picked up during these times. At South Elem, vehicles drive through traffic circle to pick up meals or walk up to distribution table to pick up meals.
** North Elementary - 815 N. 9th St. - Meals distributed 7:30a-9:00a and 11:00a-12:45p. Both breakfast and lunch may be picked up during these times. At North Elem, vehicles drive through main entrance to pick up meals or walk up to distribution table for pick up.

HONEYWELL INSTANT ALERT ON 3-18-20 ---- 
This is a message from MNCS and a request for assistance from Minnesota New Country School families: 

PLEASE PICK UP ALL BELONGINGS:
 MONDAY, MARCH 23RD OR TUESDAY, MARCH 24TH 
BETWEEN HOURS OF 7A - 7P

This is a message from MNCS and a request for assistance from Minnesota New Country School families. 

We are preparing for the possibility of an extended school closure that could go well-beyond the current closure of March 27th. Students will need to have their learning materials at home, and we would like to begin thoroughly disinfecting the school building over the next several days. In order to accomplish both of these necessary steps, we are asking elementary and high school students to retrieve all of their belongings. Both buildings will be open Monday, March 23rd and Tuesday, March 24th from 7 am to 7 pm. Only students will be allowed to enter the building.

They are encouraged to bring large containers or multiple bags to hold all personal belongings and school materials. We are asking everyone to quickly empty these spaces so that they can be thoroughly cleaned.

If a student of any age has medication in the Nurse’s Office, the student should ask the staff person on duty for that medication and they will release it to the parent or guardian outside. 

If you are unable to pick up your materials during these times, please contact your advisor or teacher to make alternate arrangements.

A note from Nurse Kathy Swenson on Wed 3-18-20 --- These guidelines will affect who will be allowed into our Elementary and High School buildings as of 3-18-20.

**UPDATED** COVID-19 Health Screening Guidelines for Childcare and Staff -- updated information from the Minnesota Department of Health (MDH) --- COVID-19 can spread from person to person even before symptoms start. So, if someone in your family starts to feel even slightly ill, run down, tired, or achy, it's important to stay home and practice "self isolation." This means limiting contact with others. If more severe symptoms develop, like a fever, cough, or shortness of breath, call your doctor. They will let you know if a COVID-19 test is needed, and what the next steps should be. If it is believed someone in your family has COVID-19, quarantine will likely be recommended. (https://www.healthychildren.org/English/health-issues/conditions/chest-lungs/Pages/Social-Distancing-Why-Keeping-Your-Distance-Helps-Keep-Others-Safe.aspx)

MInnesota Department of Health's latest guidelines: 

If you are sick with respiratory symptoms (fever, cough, sore throat, etc.) stay home for at least 7 days, and for 3 days (72 hours) with no fever or improvement of other symptoms, whichever is longer. 

If you know you were exposed to COVID-19 and feel healthy, stay home for 14 days. Symptoms may appear 2-14 days after exposure.

https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/basics.html #StayHomeMN

Update 3/16/20 at 1:15pm
	Parents and Students - both buildings plan to be open from 7 a.m. - 7 p.m. both Monday and Tuesday, March 16th and 17th. During this time, only students will be able to enter the building to gather technology needs and personal supplies and they will sign in to both buildings before entering. Parents can call ahead and be met at the door as needed. If you can’t get to the school, please contact Joan (High School) jskelly@newcountryschool.com or Trish (Elem) frontdesk@newcountryschool.com to set up a drop off at a central location in surrounding communities. Both today and tomorrow, staff will be prioritizing: Food Distribution/Plan, Childcare for Families of Emergency Care Providers, and Communications to Our Community.
	Over the next two weeks (planning period outlined in the Governor’s Executive Order prior to March 27th), educators will be creating a Distance Learning Plan for students that will be available to implement, if needed, on Monday, March 30th. 
Students may focus on school work during this planning period, if they wish, but it is not required by the closure in the Governor’s Executive Order . Instruction will begin again on March 30, 2020. 

Elem Childcare (for Emergency Workers only) starting this Wed 3-18-20 and continuing onward beyond that -- Two messages (via email) have been sent out to Elem families. If you need childcare and you are an “emergency worker” as defined by the state of MN, we need a response by 5 p.m. Monday 3-16-20 (today) for planning purposes and staffing set-up. Any childcare-related questions should go to Trish Hiscock-Austin at the Elementary (507 868-0071 x0) or taustin@newcountryschool.com


Elementary Update:
Ideas for the next two weeks -
Play outside or inside (children learn through play), Go Noodle, read for 30 minutes or more, Math around the house (measuring, cooking, telling time on an analog clock, addition, subtraction, multiplication and division practice, etc.), projects (especially 6th graders).

Letter to MNCS Families 
re: School Closure for Distance Learning Planning
Dear MNCS Families, 
Today, Governor Tim Walz and Education Commissioner Mary Cathryn Ricker announced that all Minnesota public schools will close to students starting Wednesday, March 18th. The plan is to resume instruction on Monday, March 30, 2020. 
MNCS is choosing to close beginning Monday, March 16 and Tuesday, March 17, 2020, as we are taking into account our students’ welfare. 
MNCS buildings will be open and staffed from 7am - 7pm Monday, March 16th and Tuesday, March 17th to allow students to pick up items they may need. These items could include: computers/tech, personal items, supplies/items for projects, etc. Only students and staff will be allowed in the building during this time, per Minnesota Department of Health (MDH) recommendations. Parents/Guardians choosing to pick up supplies for their student can contact their student's advisor with a list of items and coordinate a pick-up time. Parents will not be allowed to enter school buildings.
During the school closure for students, Minnesota New Country School will be joining school districts and charter schools across the state to create plans to equitably distribute distance learning to our students should we need to close schools statewide for a longer period of time due to the COVID-19 pandemic. The Minnesota Department of Education (MDE) is defining distance learning to mean that a student receives daily interaction with their licensed teacher(s) and appropriate educational materials. Starting March 30, 2020, per the instruction from the MDE, student learning will continue for the rest of the school year. 
Our educators will be giving thoughtful planning to our distance learning plan, offering careful consideration for students in a variety of areas, including students receiving special education
